title: Man attacked by shark in third incident in two days | ABC NEWS
description: A man is believed to have suffered serious injuries in a shark attack at North Steyne Beach in Manly, Sydney, shortly after 6 PM on Monday. This is the third shark attack in Sydney in just over 24 hours, following a critical incident involving a 12-year-old boy at a harbour beach in Vaucluse on Sunday. Another boy narrowly escaped injury when his surfboard was bitten at Dee Why. title: Before the RFS, Sydney in 1980 had volunteer 'bushfire brigades' | ABC NEWS
description: In 1980, the "bushfire brigade" was part of the New South Wales Bush Fire Service, a volunteer-based organisation that was the precursor to the modern NSW Rural Fire Service (NSW RFS).   The volunteer-based bushfire brigades were responsible for rural areas, while the paid, government-organised Metropolitan Fire Brigade (MFB) was primarily responsible for the Sydney metropolitan area. title: MPs deliver emotional speeches in Bondi attack condolence motions | ABC NEWS
description: Federal parliament has been recalled early for a special two-day sitting to debate new anti-hate speech and gun laws. MPs shed tears as they returned to Canberra and paid tribute to the Bondi terror attack victims during condolence motions. title: Koala population risks starvation following baby boom at Mount Lofty Ranges, study finds | ABC NEWS
description: A new study has found the koala population living in Adelaide's Mount Lofty Ranges is at an unsustainable level and could lead to starvation and death.  Researchers suggest 22 per cent of female koalas in the area to be sterilised annually to stabilise the population.  The population management program is estimated to cost $34 million over the next 25 years but the SA environment minister said she could not commit to the funding. title: Tennis stars push for better pay and conditions | The World | ABC NEWS
description: Representatives of the world's top tennis stars have been meeting with officials at the Australian Open to demand a bigger share of the tournament's revenue. The Professional Tennis Players' Association is seeking increased prize money and greater consultation over tournament scheduling, as well as more commercial freedom. Just days into this year's extravaganza, the Australian Open is already boasting record crowds and a substantial increase in its prize money. Tom Larner from Tennis Australia tells The World it wants to see players "remunerated appropriately".
